 Michael Ray Charles (review)
      
      

R. Kumasi Hampton


From:  
          Nka: Journal of Contemporary African ArtNumber 10, Spring/Summer 1999

          p. 72
        



In lieu of an abstract, here is a brief excerpt of the content:
REVIEW M I C H A E L RAY C H A R L E S Contemporary Art Center Cincinnati, Ohio Somewhere between t h e colorful, violent turf of the Dennis Rodman persona and t h e neo-slapstick Fox Network sitcom, In Living Color, lies t h e ironic sensibility and of the exhibition, "Michael Ray Charles: An American Artist, 19891997 " shown last year at t h e Contemporary A r t Center (CAC) in Cincinnati. The bruising visual discourse presented by Charles explores t h e often inponderable i s sues and questions of our culture that circulate around racial stereotypes . With his neo-expressionist manner of painting and verbal m a nipulation Charles constantly reinvents and reconfigures negative advertising stereotypes of African American characters and destroys their original debasement . His well painted scandalous broadsides are staged in a vibrant and sardonic visual language which challenges the viewer. Charles's disturbing manipulations of racial images and stereotypes, follows in t h e manner of 1997's U.S. representative to the Venice Biennale, Robert Colescott. For much of his career, Colescott has unstintingly appropriated icons of t h e Western canon and turned them on their head. And like Colescottand Kara Walker, Charles revels in t h e explosive, intercultural subtext of identity and negative stereotypes, interracial sex and race-based icons. I t is Charles's interrogation and subversion of sambos, mammies and sports/celebrity icons which move these paintings thematic thrust onto theirtroubling turf. The format Charles employs is that of an enlarged advertising banner in which a retinue of Little black Sambos, aunt J e m i m a s , pickaninnies, negro court jesters, celebrities, sports icons and black face circus animals in harlequin pants make their stage appearances . Thus, Charles's antiquesurfaced advertising "explosions" and ragged-edge graphic takeoffs are elements of his fictitious and parodic product line(s) and merchandising campaign(s): "Forever SluePerioc/,1995, from t h e series, " T h e Liberty media o n paper, courtesy of the artist. Free", "The Liberty Brothers Permanent Daily Circus" and "The Forever Free Post". Within these three artistic series Charles e m ploys a brutal parody t o d e c o n struct negative, y e t once popular, malicious American concepts used to represent t h e many ideas once originally expounded in t h e nineteenth century doctrine of Negrophobia. However, t h e c o m plexity of t h e subject Charles e x plores leads one t o ask whether his idea of transgression is a t h o r oughly worked out critique of t h e stereotype or whether it is second generation appropriation whose use value is premised on its ordinary shock value and lack of critical dimension. Whatever one Brothers Permanently Daily Circus," mixed makes of these works, it is disturbing in a way that should lead to sober evaluation of its merits rather t h a n , as many who have chosen t o castigate t h e artist do, simply dismiss i t . These alarming works go deep into neglected emotional sites where phobias reside. Michael Ray Charles's works tour these obscure locations of personal and collective memory, seeking t o unravel their incipient power and connection t o an ever present American neurosis. I n t h e paintings, we are confronted with images of such v i olence emblematic of t h e fear we all feel when recalling t h e damage inflicted by these appropriated signifiers in t h e former context. We are confronted with this again and again in t h e multi-layered visual and discursive assaults in works from t h e "Liberty Brothers Permanent Daily Circus" series. Handi the Smart Asses \s a circus ring takeoff, of a tuxedoed ringleader commanding three dancing white horses. The Greatest Blow On Earth, plays havoc with the popular promotional theme of the Barnum and Bailey circus, with a large open-mouthed negro gaping t o receive cunnilingus or perform felatio. An Army of Clowns, presents an army of exquisitely colored dancing negro clowns surging to t h e foreground. White Girl TV Dinners... 








